All they will think is that it wasn't scary, and it was ambiguous.

author: Omar Khaled

text: Beware, people: if you are going into this movie thinking it's a monster movie, YOU ARE WRONG. This trailer is very misleading (particularly the second half) in that it makes it seem that there's a ghost/entity that wants to get in and kill them or something. This is not the case. It Comes At Night is a psychological thriller about the limits of human empathy and trust, and what happens when those elements run out. Furthermore, the whole "night" motif is just a metaphor, there is no monster that comes at night. As for what really does come at night... well, I won't spoil it for you.  That being said, this movie is fantastic. It is tense and bleak, but there is a point to all of it. The acting is top-notch, the cinematography is powerful, and the movie is very moving as a whole.

text: I saw it, didn't like it. All it felt so empty that it felt like the movie was maybe 50 min when you watched it. There was no suspense, no horror, no scare. All the scary scenes are in this trailer. There was only one thing good about it, I'll put it in the spoiler.  *spoilers below*    Lost story short - Everyone gets infected and dies   More in-depth - cabin home with 3 people, 1 white guy and black woman and their son recently had to kill and burn the wife's grandpa because he go infected. Somehow he got infect but it is explained in the movie it is by contact. Anyways later on a person tries to break in and is captured, he explain him, his wife, and their kid are in a house next door, they need water so instead they decide to let them move in so they don't have to travel. Everything goes fine for a while and they get close and talk about their lives and what happened before the outbreak of the disease until the dog runs after something i the woods near the end of the movie. the dog is later found dead in front of the door and the door unlocked. it comes down to who did it. The child of the family that moved it was found lying on the group in a random room and the other kid helped him back in the room. The white guy with the black wife decides that everyone grab food and stay in their rooms separated for a couple days. it turns out the child is infect and the one family is pitted against the other eventually leading to all of the one family that moved in being killed by the other family but by them they are all exposed and they all die. the end.   Now for the interesting part. the part that makes it have that psychological thriller is "did the child actually open the door". I thought about it and if you think about it the child, even though it is portrayed in the movie that he must of opened the door and killed the dog because he was the first infected. If you think about all the events that happened, it is the black kid, the main protagonist, that might of been infected the entire time. He would constantly have nightmares of the disease and horrible things happening and these nightmares that wouldn't stop and they started after they killed the grandpa. so meaning instead of the protagonist helping the child, touching him when he helped him back to his room and got infected, it was in fact the protagonist that was infected and infected the kid. it is mentioned that the disease could take several days and time for it to appear and that in fact the protagonist might of just been more resistant to the disease. But because you never know, it's what pitted them against each other. What makes it more believable is the fact that the child couldn't of been able to open the door because it is too high and he didn't have the key were as the protagonist was tall enough and knew where the key was and had nightmares and possibly he was sleepwalking, part of the disease, and didn't realize he had killed the dog when it came back. It's possible he sees one thing when he was infected and so he just saw his dog take off but instead he had killed it. Then in one of his nights where he couldn't sleep he brought it back. That's the twist, who was the person that was really infected, the child of the family from the other house and the father lied about it to take care of his kid or the protagonist who was infected by the grandpa and didn't know it. With diseases and everyone affected differently and time to show signs, no one can know who patient zero truly was.   Now as interesting as that twist may have been, it was still not worth the price of a movie ticket. it literally had nothing to do with the night. other than possibly that the dark side affects of the disease start effecting people at night to go out at night and start causing them to do horrible things. But I was really hoping for something Blair witch style like something out in the woods was watching them and slowly finding a way to get inside and eventually does and leads them to have to high tail it out of their and run into the pitch black woods etc. that was more of what i was hoping for. all the scary scenes in the movie were just the protagonists dreams, or well nightmares.

text: Ok I just saw this movie and... Idk man. I get that we're supposed to not really know much about what's going on and the people involved because we aren't supposed to know who to trust etc. And I am fine with not knowing what caused the "outbreak" or whatever, but you can't just make an entire film and explain NOTHING! There was nothing redeeming about this movie, it was just depressing. The ending came too soon, there should have been more character development in my opinion and more leading up to the climax. I also feel like there should have been a different ending. There's no reason to make a film for the sake of being upsetting. This was fiction, not even a historical documentary or anything so there could have been at least one happy scene lol. I read an interview with the writer/creator and he talked about how his own grief inspired this movie. Ok, I get that it kind of helped you cope, but why do you want to create more macabre shit? So everyone who watches your unfinished movie can suffer along with you? The cinematography was good though, and good acting. lol but that's it.

text: Warning to all going into this.   In my opinion this was a pretty good movie, but I still left the theaters feeling dissatisfied and lied to. This is not a horror movie, nor is there nearly as much dread or tension as is portrayed in this trailer. I absolutely hate when marketing assholes decide to make trailers like this. Either give us a good idea of what the movie is actually about, or leave it a complete mystery. Don't flat out lie to the audience to draw in more viewers. This movie for what it was trying to be was bloody brilliantly made.  ‚ÄúIt Comes at Night‚Äù is a total success, building dread gradually and avoiding an overreliance on the kind of jump scares lesser films mine to absurdity. It makes ‚ÄúIt Comes at Night‚Äù less fun, but more resonant. text: The marketing of this film was all wrong. I did enjoy the final product but _only_ because I didn't see a single trailer or review beforehand.   "Horror" isn't the term I'd attach to this film, more like "psychological thriller". You get to see the impact of self-induced fear, paranoia and a lack of knowledge in its most extreme form. Very little answers are given, you're only left with fragmented information given by characters with a small grasp of reality around them, you can't even be sure that _they_ are reliable sources of information in this story. This film shows what happens when you don't know as much as you think, when trust breaks down, when you presume the worst, when fear takes over, and when you lose control of a dangerous situation. It's not about _being_ terrified by what you see, it's about how that fear controls your actions and makes you question everything.  Remember, the director wants the audience to fill in the gaps he left behind, to construct their own stories and allow the imagination to create the horror. If you're not interested in that, if you want everything handed to you on a plate, if you only want to be entertained, don't watch this.

text: This is a really decent movie. If you're into jump-scare, gore-filled, adrenaline-inducing, monster-at-every-corner movies, then this is definitely *not* the movie for you.   *Potential Spoiler Alert* This movie doesn't revolve around the monster(s), rather it revolves around how humans survive beneath the eye of predators and how one reacts to paranoia. I like that they give you ~seemingly~ insignificant information that really is important to the world-building of the storyline (AKA how they survive in a post-apocalyptic world; clean water, food, electricity, bathroom/shower, how they get rid of contaminated bodies, etcetera). The ending can seem anticlimactic to some (which I can see why), although I actually enjoyed the ending and the interpretation the viewer creates from it.

text: Let's be honest: if you didn't like this movie, then you always like your movies spoon-fed to you, and like everything neatly packaged and explained so you don't have to think too hard. This was a phenomenal movie. The real movie isn't what's seen; it's the emotions and aura it sets. If you didn't pick that up, then you probably didn't like the movie. That's fine since many people do want to be told a story with a neat plot and beginning-to-end tidiness, but this is not that movie. It's better than that.

text: One of the worst movies I've seen in a long time. What's with the idiotic title? _NOTHING_ "COMES AT NIGHT"!! A post-apocalyptic pathogen-based survival movie. Wow. THAT'S never been done before.  SPOILERS AHEAD!      The plot line was asinine. Why did the other family have to be killed? They just wanted to leave. The main family should have LET them! They would have died anyway later. And why were they shot at in the truck when they went to get the other guy's family? Who were these guys? The movie doesn't explain it at all.  We never find out just how wide-spread the plague is in the movie. We can guess that it's continent-wide or even global. But there's nothing in the movie about its origins or any real details about it, except that it's transmitted by touch and also air-born.  It had its moments, but all in all, this movie left a bad taste in my mouth.

text: The acting was great, the shots were great, it had a very indie feel to it, which I liked. The story however... I don't even know what to say about it. NOTHING i repeat, NOTHING was explained and most importantly... nothing came at night. One of the guys even says "We saw nothing", yeah me neither buddy, not one thing. What exactly was the point of this movie because I am so confused. Was it about how you lose all your humanity in such situations out of necessity to survive?  I think that's what most people would say in this movies defence but I honestly think that's a cheap excuse. Personally I think if they changed the title to something more fitting, stopped advertising the outbreak as some kind zombie thing and more of a deadly plague and stuck with the idea of a plague instead of tip-toeing around the zombie subject which literally did nothing but make the story that much more confusing and pointless. This might have been a good movie.  My biggest question is... WHAT HAPPENED TO THE DOG!?!? If this plague merely kills you (not zombify you), what the hell happened to that dog? What was he chasing? Why did he chase it? What killed him and why? The only explanation I can muster is bear. But in that case, what was the point and that's literally all you will think when you finish this movie. What was the point in any of it?

text: Woah, I didn't expect to see so much hate in the comments section. I saw the movie last night and I LOVED it! Top notch acting and camera work. It's not about the why and how of the infection, it's about (mis)trust and paranoia, and the actors carried the whole movie brilliantly. As for the title, well...  MINOR SPOILERS  1. The first time we see Will, he comes at night. 2. When the dog disappears, it comes back at night. 3. Travis' and Andrew's nightmares comes... well, at night.  I can understand people feeling let down by the lack of any explanation regarding the infection, and the lack of any actual storyline, but to me it kinda felt like Romero's Night of the Living Dead: it's not about the zombies or their origin story, it's about how people interact with each other in extreme situations, just as it is in this movie.  Don't get me wrong, the movie isn't perfect, and certainly isn't as good as Romero's NotLD. When Will and Paul go to get Will's wife and kid, it feels like there's missing footage. We don't even see Paul meeting Sarah and Andrew for the first time. That sucked. And the excessive amount of jumpscares. That sucked too. But overall, a pretty solid movie!  Then again, it's just my opinion, so who cares?

text: Overall, I found this film to be very good. The story was engaging, the performances we're top notch and the tension was there, as with most A24 horror films. However, I felt some of the artistic liberties such as messing with the aspect ratio was a tad bit on the nose of "THIS IS AN ART FILM YOU GET IT YOU SEE WHAT IM DOING? ITS ART ARGHHHH" instead of staying on the more subtle side. If the aspect ratio had been left the same, we would've had no idea what was real and what wasn't which is something that movies such as Mulholland Drive, Hereditary and Donnie Darko do with their dream/hallucination scenes. Overall, it's a decent movie and really doesn't deserve as much criticism as people give it. Something DOES come at night, and that is fear and paranoia, which is pretty great.

text: I watched it just now, even if the ending was the way it was, I enjoyed the experience of watching the movie. I loved how almost the entire movie took place in a single house, yet it felt so mysterious and interesting. 'Someone tell me whats going on?!'. The rest is a SPOILER, so be ware:   Yes, the movie gives a lot of hints and no obvious answers, but yet we all know what was going on. If you see the signs for what they are everything was quite obvious. Will lied to get his family safely into the house, maybe even already knew his boy was sick. Travis was probably sick from the beginning. He kept dreaming dreams about the affliction. (The other option is that his nightmares had no meaning at all, but who believes that). Everyone was already screwed right from the start, yet trying so hard to stay alive. Its the ultimate cynicism you could say. We're watching a group of people who are already doomed, trying to stave off their death, going through extreme lengths - even though it was inevitable right from the start. The ending was so ultimately cruel that it almost makes one laugh. Regardless, for me it was a good watch, I enjoyed it!

text: The title is a metaphor for fear and anxiety, which are a common occurrence at night. I think the film is brilliant, a very tense and scary examination of what some people will do to protect the ones they care about. It‚Äôs not false advertising, it‚Äôs just a metaphorical title. The acting is also brilliant, especially Joel Edgerton who gives one of the best performances of his career. Travis was most likely sick from the very beginning. They do say in the film that it only takes less than a day for symptoms to show. But if you really think about it, they are probably wrong and aren‚Äôt very aware of it. The nightmares and hallucinations Travis has are most likely due to the sickness. The dog is also sick, when you see the dog barking into the woods, there probably isn‚Äôt anything there. As the climax happens the aspect ratio closes in, kind of like the nightmares Travis has, his nightmares have become the stuff of reality. Also, when the other family is wanting to leave. They are concerned that Travis may be sick. As it‚Äôs implied he sleep walks, which has led many people to believe he‚Äôs the one who opened the door. As the film closes Travis dies and in the final shot, his family (who are most likely sick) what for their incoming fate. I personally love the film, it‚Äôs absolutely fine if you didn‚Äôt. However, I happen to think it‚Äôs one of the best of the decade.

text: One of the worst so-called horror movies I've ever seen.  And no, it's not because the trailer was misleading or because it's a high-brow suspense film that went over my head.  No, I fully understand that it's intended to play on paranoia and frenzied angst spiraling out of control, and that what "Comes At Night" is panic and subsequent distrust and bickering. But none of it actually built up any sense of palpable tension for me. It was... boring. No existential dread or personal anxiety was conveyed or instilled in me, the audience. It all felt empty and contrived. Didn't even craft a good story. Literally the ONLY good thing about it was Joel's acting.  This is one of those rare A24 films that completely missed the mark. If you want truly elevated, traumatic horror for the intellectual... watch Hereditary or Midsommar.

text: Spoiler Alert] It should be, "it came at night." If they didn't let Will in [who came in at night] they would have lost their son to the disease. Will [and the consequences of helping others] is the "it" in this story. This is in contrast to the social model we take for granted that helping others benefits everyone. The theme of this movie is accepting this dystopian world and the rules that govern it.  Paul displays his willingness to accept these rules by mercy-shooting his sick father-in-law to save the rest of the family. He then makes a poor decision and yields to helping out strangers, which causes the violence in his safe home and the death of his son. This is a cautionary tale leading you to the conclusion that you need to consistently respond appropriately to your environment, stockpile more ammo, and always vote for 2nd Amendment supporters! ü§£üòÇü§£

text: My thoughts about the film:  Plot: After some kind of sickness kills billions of people, some individuals resort to live in secluded areas to avoid getting sick.  A couple invites another family, who are in search of supplies, into their home despite the risk of infection.  The story revolves around what the two families will do to keep themselves healthy.   But what happens when one of them gets sick?  This film is important in our world because it's not far from fiction anymore. People are slowly dying from coronavirus.    What will people do if they know a person who has an incurable and highly contagious disease in a world where the healthcare system doesn't exist anymore?

text: Mediocre. Not bad, not good, just mediocre. I've been hearing about this movie title for years and I really expected something along the lines of The Witch, Hereditary, Midsommar, etc. But the movie tries to be a lot of things, horror, drama, thriller, romance even, but barely even scratches the surface of any of those aspects. It's weak, and it's a shame considering the current circumstances, it had so much more potential.   It's somewhat reminiscent of Cloverfield Lane, a movie that makes a better execution of immersing the viewer into the relationship that the characters develop under a lockdown of that sort.
